    content: [
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'The room is exactly the same.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Same walls. Same window. Same pale morning light that falls across the floor at exactly the angle it always did. The coffee is brewing in the kitchen. Two cups, like always — one habit that never died even when the reason for it did.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'On the wooden shelf beside my drawing table, three things sit in a row:' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'A pair of small gold earrings, the kind that catch light and turn it into something lovely.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'A thin silver bracelet, its clasp slightly worn from being undone and fastened too many times to count.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'A purple scarf, neatly folded, still carrying the faintest trace of a perfume I have not been able to name — only remember.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'People who visit this room sometimes ask about these things. I always say the same thing: they belong to someone.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'They belonged to Palak.' },
      { type: 'divider' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'I am Aarav. I am thirty-four years old. I am an architect. I design houses for people — spaces meant for living, for laughing, for the ordinary and extraordinary collisions of a shared life. I am very good at my work.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'But the only house I ever truly wanted to build... I never got to finish.' },
      { type: 'pullquote', text: 'We spend our whole lives building walls to protect ourselves, not realizing that love never knocks on doors — it simply finds the cracks.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'This is her story. And mine. And the strange, beautiful, heartbreaking place where they became the same story for a while.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Four years ago, at a wedding neither of us planned to matter, I saw a girl in a black dress standing beside the woman my best friend had just married. She was not doing anything remarkable. She was just standing there, tucking a strand of hair behind her ear, looking at the stage with something between boredom and quiet happiness on her face.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'And my whole world rearranged itself.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Just like that.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Some moments do not announce themselves. They do not come wrapped in significance. They arrive in the middle of ordinary things — a wedding, a table, a forgotten pair of earrings — and only later do you understand that this was the moment your life divided into before and after.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Before her. And after.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Her name was Palak. She had ocean blue eyes that I thought I had imagined, until the second time I looked. She laughed with her whole face. She forgot things — earrings, bracelets, scarves — as if she was always leaving small pieces of herself behind for the world to find.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'I found them. I kept every single one.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'I did not know then that she was doing the same with time. Leaving pieces of it behind. Slowly, invisibly, beautifully — until there was none left.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'But I am getting ahead of myself.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Let me begin where all the best stories begin.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'At a wedding. In the light. When I first saw her.' },
    ],
