    title: 'The Farewell — and After',
    teaser: 'When it was time for Priya to leave with Nikhil, the women who had known her longest began to cry.',
    wordCount: 920,
    readTimeMinutes: 5,
    content: [
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'When it was time for Priya to leave with Nikhil, the women who had known her longest began to cry.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'This is one of the things I have always found both beautiful and unbearable about Indian weddings — the farewell. The bride\'s side weeping. The groom\'s side waiting. The particular quality of grief that is not grief exactly but the acknowledgment that something has changed, that a chapter has closed even as a new one opens.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Priya\'s mother was inconsolable. Her younger cousin was clinging to her arm. Even the woman who had been managing the decorations was dabbing at her eyes.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Palak was standing among them, and she was crying too — not loudly, not dramatically, but with the quiet, real quality of someone who genuinely loved the person leaving.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'I found myself walking toward the group.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: '"Please," I said, and they all looked at me — this man in a black suit who had appeared from America without warning, now inserting himself into this most tender of moments. "You are not sending her to a random place, to a random person. I have known Nikhil since we were eight years old. I know him better than anyone in this room. He will take care of her like she is the most precious thing in his life — because she is." I paused. "And uncle and aunty will treat her like their own daughter. She is not just Nikhil\'s wife. She is already my elder sister. Don\'t worry. If something ever goes wrong, I am also there."' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'I had perhaps slightly overcommitted. But I meant every word.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'The crying did not stop exactly, but it changed quality — became softer, more accepting. Some people laughed through their tears.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'I caught Palak\'s eyes across the group. She was looking at me with an expression that I could not entirely read — something between surprise and something else, something warmer, something she tucked away quickly when she realized I had noticed.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'I leaned slightly toward her and said, quietly enough that only she could hear: "Please don\'t cry. Pretty girls shouldn\'t cry."' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'She looked down immediately. A flush of colour along her cheekbones. A smile she was clearly fighting.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: '"And if you keep crying," I added, "we\'ll have to take you with us."' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'She laughed out loud. So did several people nearby who had heard. Nikhil, standing at the car, caught my eye and raised an eyebrow with a look that said: really?' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'I shrugged.' },
      { type: 'pullquote', text: 'Humour is not the opposite of emotion. It is sometimes the only way to honour how deeply you feel without drowning in it.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'In the car, on the way back, I sat in the front seat driving while Nikhil and Priya sat in the back. The night had that particular Indian quality — warm despite the December chill, the streets still full of life even at this hour, the kind of night that feels like it should be the setting of something important.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'I glanced in the rearview mirror and found Priya looking at me with a knowing expression.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: '"So," she said. "Palak."' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: '"What about Palak?"' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: '"You like her."' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: '"I just met her."' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: '"Aarav. I watched you watch her for three hours. You forgot to eat dinner."' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'I had, in fact, forgotten to eat dinner. I had not noticed until this moment.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: '"She\'s very nice," I said, with great dignity.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Nikhil made a sound that was somewhere between a cough and a laugh.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: '"Will she come to the reception?" I asked, trying and failing to sound casual.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Priya paused. A beat too long. "Hmm. Maybe not. She might be busy."' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'My heart sank slightly.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'In the back seat, visible in the mirror, Priya met Nikhil\'s eyes. He pressed his lips together, suppressing a smile. She had already invited Palak. She was enjoying this enormously.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'I drove home through the December night, one hand on the wheel, the other in my jacket pocket where two small gold earrings sat quietly in the dark.' },
      { type: 'pullquote', text: 'The things we carry in our pockets are often the things we are not yet ready to admit we want to keep.' },
    ],
